When the housing bubble burst, the financial institutions holding these mortgage-backed securities suffered greatly. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt in 2007, representing roughly 30% of the nation's GDP. Ultimately, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at low prices, Lehman Brothers was dissolved, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were compelled to become commercial banks subject to stringent regulations. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac held $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition—the part of your narrative that can either be a soaring showcase of your writing talents or the segment that causes readers to drift off or abandon your work altogether. Dr. Merlin, for instance, often finds herself exasperated when encountering excessive details, particularly when they aren't engaging.

Exposition can be a tricky element.

Most seasoned readers are familiar with the advice to "Show, don't tell," yet Dr. Merlin occasionally ends up with lengthy sections where little happens, or too much does. Exposition is that mischievous voice that suggests explaining the background to get to the exciting parts (distinct from the other voice that insists on detailing every aspect of each character's past).

Exposition involves informing the audience about events, generally through straightforward prose. In movies, it occurs when one character relays a significant amount of information to another, reminiscent of "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In literature, it's the author who conveys this information.

To illustrate, imagine reading a story where you're informed that the heroine met her partner at a specific place and time, they married in a grand ceremony, and then her husband was tragically killed in front of her. You wouldn't anticipate this entire narrative to be condensed into two pages, with minimal dialogue. You'd expect the author to delve into the husband's character, showcasing his love through his actions and words, and similarly, you'd want to see how the heroine's life was enriched by his presence. A detailed portrayal of the husband's character would allow you to feel invested in his fate and offer insights into the heroine's personality: what she cherished in him, the strength of their connection, and glimpses into her thoughts and dreams mirrored through his perspective. This emotional depth would make you grieve his loss alongside her, deepening your connection to her journey.

In essence, you'd anticipate a richer narrative beyond the bare storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, it's crucial to add depth to your story. (*considers metaphor, continues undeterred*) It's sometimes tempting to gloss over certain elements. Maybe you're introducing a new character, and you know he once served in the Air Force, now manages a gas station at night, was married twice, has no children, enjoys weekend fishing, secretly hopes to own the gas station, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, broadcast live, was NBC 4 on the morning of August 13, 2011. The main story involved a man named Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife, although her name wasn't mentioned. They showed his mug shot, which portrayed him as quite menacing. The coverage of this developing story lasted about two minutes, which seemed appropriate. The details shared were limited to the fact that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been taken into custody.

The second segment covered a shooting incident involving an 18-year-old named Travis Buyers. He was critically injured in the Sharon Woods area, with no arrests or suspects at the time. The SWAT Team was looking into the matter. The brevity of this report stood out, possibly because it involved a black individual in a predominantly black neighborhood. It has been my observation over the years that crimes involving minority victims do not receive the same level of attention as those involving white individuals. For instance, when a white child or adult is kidnapped or harmed, the media coverage is extensive, whereas minority cases often receive minimal mention.

Another story discussed a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. The report included details about the location of the incident, identifying the bullet as a .22 caliber from a rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a reward of five thousand dollars for information leading to the arrest of the shooter.

The forecast segment outlined rain and thunderstorms expected on Saturday afternoon, with weekend temperatures predicted to be in the mid to low eighties. Although brief, this segment seemed intended as a "teaser" to keep viewers engaged.

Coverage also included a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The suspect, described as a dark-skinned black man, was wearing a hoodie. He was approximately six feet tall and weighed around 150 pounds. The emphasis on his skin color and its darkness seemed unusually pronounced.

Another report featured Rene Rodriguez, a convicted drug kingpin from Texas, who was found guilty of conspiring to distribute large quantities of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. Interestingly, instead of stating he received a 25-year prison sentence, they mentioned "300 months," possibly to make it sound harsher. They also highlighted that he was Hispanic, a detail that appeared irrelevant to the core of the story.

An exchange traded fund (ETF) is a type of investment vehicle that aims to mirror the performance of a specific index, commodity, or collection of assets, much like an index fund. However, unlike index funds, ETFs offer greater flexibility because they can be bought and sold like individual stocks on an exchange. One of the advantages of ETFs is that they combine the broad market exposure of index funds with the flexibility of stock trading, allowing investors to engage in practices such as short selling, buying on margin, and purchasing in small quantities, even as little as a single share. While these features are appealing, ETFs generally have lower expense ratios compared to the average mutual fund. On the downside, trading ETFs incurs commission fees similar to those associated with stock trades. Additionally, ETFs provide a vast array of fund choices. Despite these advantages, a prudent investor should critically assess whether the proclaimed benefits, like diversification, are truly present and to what degree. For this discussion, we will analyze the ETF IHF by comparing it with its top 10 underlying holdings, aiming to evaluate if owning a single ETF can match the benefits of holding a diversified set of the ten individual stocks. We will also explore if there are alternative configurations of these stocks that could yield a more favorable Sharpe ratio or return.

To streamline the analysis, we will focus on the top ten holdings, which represent 63.58% of the ETF’s total assets. These holdings and their respective asset percentages are outlined below.

By examining the proportion of assets attributed to these ten stocks and adjusting them to a normalized 100%, we can estimate their contributions to a portfolio's Beta and Return, assuming the portfolio consists solely of these stocks in the same proportions as those in the ETF. The chart below details the calculated Beta and return.

The chart indicates that a portfolio restricted to the top 10 holdings achieves a return that is 6.11% higher than that of the ETF, translating to a 16% improvement in returns. Furthermore, the Beta of these top ten holdings is lower by 0.12 compared to the ETF overall. The findings suggest that a portfolio of the top 10 holdings might offer higher returns with a reduced Beta. Nonetheless, it's possible that the average returns of these two portfolios do not differ significantly in statistical terms. To determine the statistical significance of any differences, we calculate and normalize the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks to 100%, allowing us to compare their collective standard deviation against that of the ETF IHF.

Examining Figure 17, it becomes evident that there was a significant decline in the submissions of commuter logs during the project's third month. This was somewhat discouraging, and pinpointing the exact cause is challenging. The arrival of winter at a New England campus likely contributes to fewer people commuting by bike or on foot, which could partially explain the drop-off. December also signifies the conclusion of the fall semester, a time when individuals are engrossed in completing assignments, grading, and other academic tasks. Consequently, logging commutes might not have been a priority for many. Moreover, December ushers in the busy holiday season and a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to visit the campus. Classes resume in late January for the spring semester, possibly another reason for the low log entries that month. Nevertheless, this doesn't fully account for the low submissions in February. It's plausible that projects like this start with enthusiasm that wanes over time. To counteract this, we introduced the Carpool Challenge Week in March, a focused campaign aimed at revitalizing the project, which resulted in an increase in log submissions. Thus, a key challenge was sustaining project momentum amid a natural dip in engagement and the specific issue of holiday and semester breaks typical in higher education.

Another obstacle for this or any alternative commuting project is the widespread preference for the autonomy and convenience of driving personal vehicles, a deeply ingrained cultural norm. Therefore, providing incentives for alternative commuting methods is crucial. We awarded numerous prizes, including gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, a local independent bookstore, and some larger national chains. It would have been intriguing to observe how offering more substantial prizes, such as a new bicycle, hybrid car, or electric vehicle, might have influenced participation, potentially addressing the drop in engagement. The prize structure remained consistent throughout the project. However, increasing the value of the prizes over time might have encouraged continued participation. While the initial gift cards were adequate, announcing additional prizes like bicycles in December and a hybrid or electric car in January could have spurred greater engagement.

While exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all the trick films, numbering fifteen from the years 1895 to 1901. These films cleverly employ creative editing to create illusions. My analysis primarily involved detailing the stylistic elements prevalent in most trick films and investigating the unique characteristics of some of the later works. Typically, trick films from this era are staged, filmed within a static, frontal proscenium setup, avoid camera movement, utilize long and medium shots, and adhere to a strict one shot equals one film principle. However, some films from the start of the twentieth century challenge these norms by introducing elements like multiple shots.

A key feature shared by trick films is their filming on an indoor set framed by a frontal proscenium. The camera remains stationary, not tracking any movement of figures or objects. This composition style was prevalent in early filmmaking, rooted in theatrical traditions and, specifically for trick films, in vaudeville and magic performances. The stage setting inherently restricts movement, with figures in trick films typically only moving laterally without advancing towards or retreating from the camera. For instance, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors appear from the right and move horizontally. Even when they exit the frame, the camera does not follow.

The frontal proscenium format also dictates the use of long shots and occasionally medium shots, with close-ups absent from Edison’s trick films. This mirrors the theatrical and vaudeville custom, where audiences observed the entire act at once, confined within the stage’s borders. As with many early films, actors remain in the middle distance, avoiding movement towards the camera, thus eliminating the need for close-ups.

Most early trick films generally conform to the principle that one conceptual shot represents an entire film. This confines their duration to roughly a minute or less, contingent on the frames per second. It also restricts the narrative or dramatic scope, with many focusing on brief vaudeville-style tricks like magic, vanishing acts, and transformations with minimal storyline. It’s important to note, however, that in a trick film, what appears as a single conceptual shot to the audience may actually consist of several shots seamlessly combined to create illusions of appearing or disappearing. For instance, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), closer examination reveals the point where the scene with Mary’s severed "head" begins, despite the film being perceived as a single shot by the viewer.

Ian Watt, in his work The Rise of the Gothic Novel, refers to the "Gothic Novel" as an "oxymoron for 'Old-New.'" This literary form has been regarded in various ways—some dismiss it, others extol its virtues, and opinions differ on its depth and the 'terrible sublime' quality it purportedly possesses, as observed by Burke. The inception of this genre can be traced back to Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, which blended elements from both "ancient" and "modern" romances to forge a new path in literary expression. Walpole incorporated "old" theatrical techniques with 'new' naturalistic elements of contemporary novels to craft what he called "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre harks back to medieval theatre, architecture, and customs. Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, "gothic" was a term applied to a variety of peoples, styles, and eras, often viewed as outdated or unsophisticated against the backdrop of "modern" societal and literary progress. The fusion of theatrical "Gothic" elements with the novel's format, which offers readers a more intimate understanding of characters' psychology, is what has allowed the Gothic genre to persist over time, simultaneously appearing outdated and fresh to readers far removed from its origins.

A significant theme in Gothic novels is the notion of Chivalry. This medieval concept, which encompasses the training of a knight, is both preserved and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry holds particular significance for Gothic authors due to what it symbolizes—the archetypal knight, courageous, honorable, and skilled—and the perceived absence of these qualities in their contemporary society, especially noted by Walpole. By incorporating chivalric ideals and behaviors, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized, hinting at the future development of Gothic into Romantic literature, and serves as a means to critique and potentially elevate the present. When Walpole crafted The Castle of Otranto, he was navigating a politically turbulent era, filled with uncertainty about the future. Engulfed in political machinations and arguably unjust accusations, he might have begun to perceive, even if subconsciously, that the moral integrity and innate "goodness" associated with the gothic era were absent in the individuals of his own time. This notion is evident in characters like Frederic. Before even encountering Frederic, the reader learns that he embodies numerous chivalric qualities; he is depicted as:

Frederic is portrayed using an abundance of traditional chivalric imagery; most notably, he is a prince who has endured suffering and tragedy, having left and believed to be slain by infidels. The depiction of the "gallant and courteous Knight" is, of course, an exaggeration, introducing the soon-to-be Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management encompasses a series of processes that facilitate the movement of goods from the initial customer order through stages such as raw materials acquisition, supply, production, and ultimately distribution to the end customer. The concept of supply chain management was introduced in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant, who articulated it as the comprehensive process of organizing, executing, and overseeing operations within the supply chain to effectively fulfill customer demands. This management framework consists of six critical components: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information, which are leveraged by business managers to optimize customer service delivery.

The production phase marks the beginning of the supply chain journey. It serves as the cornerstone for the entire supply chain operation. During this phase, decisions are made regarding the timing, rationale, location, and method of production. Managers must ascertain customer preferences, which can be achieved by analyzing market trends, as the market serves as a significant indicator of consumer demands. Once managers have evaluated the market and grasped customer needs, they can determine which products to manufacture and the quantities required. Subsequently, decisions are made about the production site, choosing the most suitable plant to achieve the desired volume and quality of goods, ensuring customer satisfaction is prioritized. Once the production site is selected, managers then focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. The production stage is crucial in the supply chain process, where meticulous planning is essential to avoid potential time and financial losses. For instance, during my tenure at Wal-Mart and Target, both organizations had detailed layouts and procedures for every facet of the business, from employee attire to receiving shipments. Such structured processes ensure smooth operations and clarity in roles and expectations.

Supply is the second fundamental component of supply chain management. It involves making strategic decisions to define the core capabilities of a facility and forming outsourcing partnerships based on these decisions. A company may have multiple production divisions for a single product, each equipped with different machinery, staff, and expertise. It is the manager's responsibility to determine which division is best suited for various product processes. Additionally, management may opt to outsource tasks to other companies, primarily to enhance velocity. Velocity refers to the ability to deliver quality and adaptability while simultaneously minimizing costs or maintaining low expenditure levels.

Victorian novels are often noted for their meticulous detailing and focus on the upper echelons of society during that era. However, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, while considered Victorian, depart from this norm. Both incorporate elements of mystery and the unusual, which are not typical of their time, to deepen the portrayals of their characters and offer insights into their motivations and emotional states.

A striking example from Oliver Twist illustrates this: “And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” (Dickens, 220)

These novels frequently use mysterious elements like dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the specifics differ in each case. In Oliver Twist, such occurrences often unveil aspects of Oliver's psyche, his suffering, and his understanding of the reality surrounding him. When the incident of Oliver being shot is revisited in chapter 28, he re-experiences it intensely, as if dreaming, while desperately seeking help. This passage emphasizes Oliver's lack of control over the events, highlighting his precarious health condition through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The overwhelming nature of the shooting numbs his senses, leaving him unaware of the “unseen hand” that rescues him; he endures his misery again, with pain now tied to fear rather than surprise. This raises questions about whose actions led to his plight, as it certainly wasn't his own doing. The shooting underscores Oliver's powerlessness, showing his inability to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is at stake. The text hints at a growing sense of submission in Oliver, as if Fagin’s influence is wearing him down, making him accept his despair and affecting his capacity to respond. Otherwise, it would seem that Oliver would attempt to act, if only to preserve his own life.

“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting ours.”

A few years back, I was involved in an after-school program where I tutored elementary students. My role was to assist them in the subjects they found challenging, though I was particularly skilled in English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to work with a young boy named Adrian, who was likely in third or fourth grade and having significant difficulties with reading. I noticed something unusual; he could pronounce some letters flawlessly, while others were a complete struggle. Despite being of Latino descent, Adrian spoke English perfectly. Our challenges continued until I met his mother while supervising a small group of students left behind during a field trip. Adrian's mother spoke only Spanish. Despite my limited Spanish skills, we managed to communicate, and it suddenly became clear: Adrian's issue wasn't with reading itself, but rather with his grasp of the English alphabet. I can't say for sure if this insight helped him, but I sincerely hope he's improved.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier issue prevalent in schools, especially in California. It illustrates how this barrier isn't always apparent. Even a child fluent in spoken English can face significant hurdles in reading. Recognizing the problem is straightforward, but finding solutions is another matter. For Adrian, focused tutoring on English reading, particularly the alphabet and pronunciation, was the answer. However, for many children who speak little English, the solution is more complex. No single approach, be it dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, or ESL classes, can solve this issue alone. The key is to integrate all these methods.

The dual language system, in particular, is a promising strategy. It's beneficial not only for Spanish-speaking children but for all students. Research shows that children in bilingual programs often outperform their peers. Despite concerns that such programs are resource-intensive and offer little benefit to the majority, this is a misconception. Implementing these programs universally would benefit all students. The challenge is in execution. Should we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that's impractical. However, there is no reason why we can't have bilingual aides or tutors to support this initiative.

From a young age, many of us are introduced to the idea that there exists something greater than ourselves, something beyond our understanding. Some attend Sunday school to learn about it, others visit temples, or seek answers within their own hearts. Many people embrace the religious beliefs passed down by their families. Yet, some choose to reject these beliefs, insisting there's nothing beyond their personal, self-centered reality. We might adopt a particular set of values, only to later shift to another. Regardless of the path we take, we embark on a journey to define a part of ourselves through our individual views on spirituality. We seek a guiding light to lead us from darkness into brightness.

"A cardinal," my dad replied when I asked him about his favorite bird. We were sitting on our front porch, listening to the rain pounding on the metal roof above as we shared a smoke. The downspouts directed the rain, overwhelming the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain, a look that seemed both searching and reminiscent. Over the past few months, he had become thinner, with his clothes hanging loosely on him. His hair had thinned as well, more so than I remembered. He continued to avoid eye contact, staring into the rain. I felt isolated, scared, unable to express to my dad how much I would miss him, fearing that discussing it would make it all too real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer, and joined him in looking out at the rain falling in the June evening.

Later that year, in December, my father passed away, just five days after I turned twenty-two. The treatments hadn't eased his pain but had extended his life slightly beyond what doctors had predicted. I couldn't find any value in prolonging his suffering. I wondered what kind of God would allow this. Alone in the night, I didn't pray. If God existed, it seemed to me that he had stopped listening long ago.

I didn't want to see him transition from this life to whatever lay beyond, so I chose not to be there. I couldn't witness the end of the life that had given me mine. I wanted to remember my father for how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I understood him better than anyone else, even better than his family, and knew he wouldn't want his only child witnessing his death. I curled up in bed for three days, waiting for the inevitable news.

No one even reached out to me.

John Taylor of Caroline was a fervent advocate of Republicanism in its early days. Although primarily an agriculturist, his time in politics and dedication to personal liberty and governance made him a notable figure. Taylor's commitment to an agrarian lifestyle was central to his views on government. His efforts to safeguard and promote what he saw as the noblest profession influenced his perspectives on sovereignty, constitutional matters, and the judiciary.

Taylor believed that the United States had a unique chance to establish an exemplary system, free from the constraints of native traditions that could impede the creation of self-governance. He was a firm believer in the natural rights of individuals, asserting that these rights are interconnected; the denial of one compromises the rest, diminishing their value. Thus, he argued that these rights should remain untouched by governmental authority. He contended that what some referred to as the "state of nature" allowed those with strength and cunning to prosper, a situation that civilization should not replicate.

To achieve this ideal society, Taylor argued for a government that acknowledges both the good and evil inherent in humanity. He held firm views on dual morality, stating that "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He identified good principles as those that safeguard private property, enhance agriculture, and curb capitalism, believing that a government rooted in these principles would operate justly, even if led by self-interest and greed. He saw self-interest as the driving force behind human actions, only deemed negative when it fostered societal divisions that benefited some at the expense of others. A well-structured government was essential to restrain man's inherent evil, requiring vigilant oversight to prevent the adoption of harmful principles.

Like other committed Republicans of his era, Taylor advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He favored a highly restricted Federal government, granted only the powers explicitly outlined in the Constitution. He understood that a large Federal government could be costly and potentially tyrannical. Nonetheless, he recognized the risks of a straightforward, literal approach and warned that ignoring the framers' intent could lead to corruption. He also regarded the Declaration of Independence as the true foundational document of the United States, as it more clearly defines the nation as a collective of sovereign states rather than a single entity.

I looked down, my mind taking in the scene before me with a detached calmness. Quietly and without emotion, my practiced awareness observed without trying to connect the scene to any larger concept, my mind processing the image I beheld. Thoughts entered and exited my mind almost quicker than they arrived. My consciousness operated so smoothly that it felt as though I had no independent thoughts, just a fluid and active experience of the sight before me. 

Once, following advice from an artist I knew, I bought a book titled The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I had been eager to learn drawing since I was six, and the book covers everything from understanding a pencil to how the brain interprets lines. One method it suggested was using a square frame to focus on any picture the artist wanted to examine. This approach turned a complex scene, like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room, into a simpler image of a bowl of fruit on a flat surface. 

At that moment, looking at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally apply the artist’s frame. I was too overwhelmed, too awed, and could only stand there in wonder. Picasso had his blue period, Monet had a passion for greenery, and the Italian Renaissance masters reveled in color. If I aspired to call my perspective Artistic, then here lay the beginnings of my work, the start of my narrative, Work in Brown.

My fingers touched my chosen artistic tool, muscles tensing and relaxing as my hand moved, my mind's intention taking shape in what might have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled calmly and smoothly, clear and pristine. Flakes of matter broke away and disappeared. My muscles tensed, my hand more quickly and anxiously hit the toilet handle again. The stubborn brown object remained, stuck like a slug at the bottom of the toilet. 

Holding the mop loosely, feet planted firmly, green tie uncomfortably tight around my neck, I frowned at the offensive bundle of processed materials someone had left for those of us cleaning the bathrooms at Rite Aid. After a few more flushes and a few more moments of introspection, my hand reached for the toilet paper, wrapping it around until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly submerged into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

The issue of teenage fatalities in car accidents is a growing concern. Various elements contribute to the alarming statistics associated with young drivers in the United States. According to the National Institutes of Health, one aspect of this problem is that teenagers' brains are not fully developed to manage the dangers of driving. Additionally, lack of experience significantly contributes to the issue, leading not just to more fatal accidents but also a higher incidence of rollovers, speeding, and other road mishaps. 

Moreover, teenagers are at greater risk when driving with friends, a common scenario. Research from the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center highlights a connection between the age of passengers and the frequency of traffic accidents.

In response, states like California have introduced provisional licenses for teens, which impose restrictions on driving hours and carrying minor passengers. However, I believe these measures are merely temporary solutions. The root problem is that young drivers, based on statistical evidence, are generally unprepared to manage the responsibilities and risks of driving. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman argues that even 18 might be too young for a full driver's license. His research, discussed by USA Today, indicates that individuals under 19-20 often seek risky thrills. Delaying the age for obtaining a driver's license could reduce these risks as the propensity for thrill-seeking diminishes.

Without changes, we risk seeing an increase in fatal accidents as more young drivers take to the roads, especially as the children of the Baby Boomer generation become eligible for licenses by 2010. Implementing legislation to address this is relatively straightforward. Schools could still offer driver’s education to start training future drivers, but operating a vehicle could be restricted to those 18 and older. Provisional permits could be granted before full licenses, with a specified number of training hours required. This requirement could align with existing state standards, such as California’s current 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.

Considering the widespread nature of this issue, uniform national legislation would be a sensible and effective strategy to protect teenagers nationwide. The concept of such legislation is not new, but it is a necessary step.

This document explores three primary aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, it offers a concise definition of the disorder. Then, it delves into the diagnostic process, highlighting typical traits or "red flags." Lastly, it discusses strategies that teachers in mainstream classroom settings can employ to support students with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is described as the proficiency and effectiveness with which the central nervous system (CNS) interprets auditory information. More specifically, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information within the CNS and the neurobiological activity that supports this processing, leading to electrophysiologic auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). Essentially, it is a condition where the brain cannot properly process auditory input. Individuals with CAPD typically have normal hearing and are not classified as "hearing impaired." However, the brain region responsible for distinguishing words or differentiating between speech and background noise does not operate in the usual manner.

The earliest reference to what would become known as CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, when it was termed "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) during studies of children with communicative disorders. In 1954, an Italian research team led by Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children. Subsequently, in 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing and developed a model to explain the physiology of the central auditory nervous system (CANS) underlying dichotic perception (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 spurred further research on children with CAPD.

CAPD can present in various forms: individuals may struggle to localize or perceive sound in space, have difficulty distinguishing between different "acoustic events," fail to recognize sound patterns, or be unable to detect changes in speech, such as sarcasm conveyed through vocal tone. Additionally, one sound may mask another, subsequent sound, and individuals might lack the capability to synthesize auditory cues into meaningful interpretations that guide their actions. They may also be challenged in recalling the sequence of auditory information (Ferre).

Diagnosing CAPD requires a thorough screening, involving "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function." This process might be handled by audiologists, speech-language pathologists (SLPs), psychologists, and other professionals using a variety of measures that assess auditory-related skills (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). These evaluations could include questionnaires, surveys, and observations of auditory behaviors, particularly how individuals respond to specific stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test with a high rate of diagnostic accuracy, and the disorder's cause remains unknown. Many diagnostic procedures involve presenting patients with multiple, concurrent auditory stimuli, asking them to identify specific items such as a sequence of words or numbers. More advanced diagnostics may involve measuring acoustic signals within the ear and recording the responses to these signals.

I am eager to pursue a career in social work, specifically with the Division of Family and Children Services, with the aim of assisting children who have experienced abuse or neglect and offering support to families in crisis. I bring to the field of social work a dedication to service, a deep respect for others, a commitment to ethical practice, and a resolve to foster better relationships while continually enhancing my professional skills. These values are not only essential to the profession of social work but are also deeply significant to me on a personal level.

Since childhood, I've been drawn to helping others, though I was initially uncertain about which career path would best fulfill this aspiration. During my high school and college years, I observed many people avoiding their problems and some adopting less-than-ideal coping strategies. Witnessing these situations influenced my decision to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. After graduating from Piedmont College in 2009, still unsure of my career direction, I took some time to reflect. That summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy who was visibly anxious. She explained that he was trying to escape an abusive home. The next day, he reported his parents to the authorities. Feeling compelled to help, I visited his parents' home and expressed my concerns to the police, mentioning my recent degree in Psychology. The police asked me to speak with the parents as legal intervention was not an option for the teen. In conversation, the parents appeared uneasy and attempted to justify their son’s actions. This experience profoundly impacted me and led me to seriously consider a career in social work, focusing on resolving family disputes.

Another crucial value in social work is social justice. Our society often claims to value individuals, yet paradoxically, pressures them to conform. This contradiction has always puzzled me, as I value my individuality and resist societal pressures to conform. Throughout my high school and college years, I actively opposed social injustice by expressing myself through unique hair colors and clothing, advocating for LGBTQ+ rights through the Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance, and standing against racism and discrimination. I am committed to promoting social justice and will continue to challenge social injustices wherever I encounter them.

This paper explores the Biological and Sociocultural frameworks in the context of insomnia. The biological framework examines inherited genetic factors and medical health aspects, while the Sociocultural framework considers environmental interactions and their implications for race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review analyzes insomnia by discussing these frameworks and detailing selected research to elucidate and enhance the understanding of each model. The research explanations and findings are subsequently evaluated to highlight their particular strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be categorized as primary sleep disorders, disorders related to another mental condition, or those associated with other issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, whereas disorders linked to another mental condition relate to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorders may arise from medical issues or substance use. Dyssomnias encompass Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves difficulties with initiating or maintaining sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia concerns staying awake, both persisting for at least one month. Narcolepsy features cataplexy and/or automatic REM. While Dyssomnias are primarily about sleep initiation and maintenance, Parasomnias are related to behavioral or physiological abnormalities during sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders linked to another mental disorder involve sleep challenges due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review primarily focuses on insomnia and, to some extent, on primary sleep disorders in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genetic, heritable, and physiological factors. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin play a role in regulating sleep and wakefulness. A study conducted on mice found that phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons are crucial for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor triggers responses that encourage sleep, while inhibition of its firing can reduce anxiety and promote sleep. The GABAB agonist baclofen was found to increase sleep duration (Matsuki et al., 2009). These findings suggest that mouse models can be extrapolated to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for the GABAB receptor in humans. An issue or absence of this receptor could impact one's ability to sleep without medication. The sociocultural dimension of this study implies that if the phenotype were inherited, it could manage sleep, and any alteration of the receptor would naturally disrupt sleep, affecting aspects of life such as education, work, and daily activities requiring focus and routine.

I've been attending University Park for around two and a half years now, which amounts to four and a half semesters. Navigating the campus can be challenging for many students, myself included. During my freshman year, I was assigned a dorm in East Halls, located at the far eastern edge of the campus, apart from the stadium and the Bryce Jordan Center. Commuting from Stuart Hall to classes in distant locations like the Willard building, near the campus center, could take as long as 25 minutes on foot, particularly in bad weather, which is common in State College. A conversation with a recent alum revealed that not too long ago, the East Halls dorms were isolated by large expanses of unused land. Today, those areas have been developed into sports fields, significant new structures such as the new Creamery and health services building, and are now encircled by apartments. As the campus continues to grow, moving from one place to another becomes increasingly challenging. What could be the most effective solution for mobility issues on a college campus? The answer lies in bicycles. However, simply having bikes won't resolve the problem. Students need to use them, and the campus infrastructure must accommodate cyclists' needs.  
A friend of mine, who recently started biking again after several years, brought up an interesting point. He said, "Bikes are fantastic. For a while, it wasn't considered cool to ride one, but it's really the best way to get around." Besides promoting physical fitness, cycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. With just a bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort, you can cover 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I currently live off-campus, just as far from the campus center as some dorms. My smartest decision this year was purchasing a bike. I have a class in the Thomas building every day, which is a good twenty-five-minute walk from where I live. Cycling can reduce that time to just 5 minutes if I pedal quickly enough. The challenge lies in Pollock Road, the most direct route to the Thomas building from my home, which can be difficult to navigate, with or without a bike. While walking has its advantages, my schedule is too packed for that. Without my bike, walking would be my only dependable way to get to class, adding an extra 30-40 minutes to my day for a walk to Thomas. That equates to over two and a half hours each week. On top of that, there’s all the additional walking time to other classes and appointments. It's more time than I can afford to lose.

In the novel Brave New World, Aldous Huxley critiques the looming dangers posed by technology and the capitalist framework that supports it by depicting a dystopian society. In this world, the collective is prioritized over the individual, and from birth, people are conditioned to seek immediate gratification above everything else. The citizens are portrayed as mere instruments in a larger scheme, adhering to a single ideology as directed by the World Controller. Through a Marxist lens, one can discern Huxley's skepticism regarding the evolution of these systems. Terms commonly used in Marxism, such as hegemony and reification, bolster the notion that Huxley's work critiques the flaws of the economic landscape of his era.

Capitalism is caricatured through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. Essentially, ordinary citizens are kept from understanding their true economic relationships with other classes, focusing instead on personal gain. This is attributed to the ideological control of the working class, made evident by the conditioning in Brave New World. The lower classes, such as Deltas and Gammas, lack genuine autonomy; hypnopaedia intensifies their urge to consume, spend, and indulge. This manipulation is orchestrated, as mentioned, by the World Controller. Hegemony, the complete dominance of social groups by another, is clearly applied here. The lower classes remain oblivious to their manipulation, literally buying into an ideology supporting this structure, namely capitalism and consumerism. The upper classes can recognize it but remain passive; few Alphas or Betas, aside from characters like Bernard, challenge their status. The interactions among social classes, as will be further examined, highlight capitalism's perceived oppression.

In Brave New World, relationships between different individuals do not exist. The novel seemingly avoids distinguishing characters—even major ones lack depth. Huxley might be suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together strip individuals of free will and self-expression. Love and extreme emotions are absent; interactions are superficial, depicted through the way men talk about women, focusing mainly on their physical attributes, and women openly discuss their experiences. Moreover, each class's contentment with their hierarchical placement reveals capitalism's socioeconomic impact. Their strict adherence to their communal roles reflects Marxist views on the proletariat, who are mistakenly convinced of their superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform with their peers.

Nearly four years ago, I enrolled in a course on Islam at CBC. A central topic of intense debate in the class was the perception of Islam as either a peaceful or hostile religion. I find this question even more pertinent today than before. Reflecting on the period since 9/11, I've noticed a shift in the media's portrayal of Islam—from an initially antagonistic stance towards Islamic extremism to a more tolerant approach within America. In 2001, it seemed unlikely to have a presidential candidate like Barack Obama, whose family has connections to Islam.

The Prophet's biography captivates me because, based on my understanding of Muhammad's history, it contradicts his portrayed character. Previously, I believed Muhammad compelled people to embrace Islam, conquering tribes and imposing the religion upon them. However, the biography presents Muhammad as a misunderstood figure, almost martyr-like, who humbly engaged with others. It describes how individuals gradually recognized the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

Additionally, there are striking resemblances between the ministries of Jesus and the purported miracles of Muhammad. A notable example is when he allegedly multiplied mutton and milk to feed forty men. This narrative style suggests that the authors intended to depict Muhammad as a modest prophet who embodied truth and performed miracles without needing to prove himself. I find this problematic as it diminishes the miracles and life of Jesus Christ, seemingly borrowing from Jesus's legacy through Muhammad.

Moreover, numerous stories in the biography seem designed to demonstrate instances of voluntary conversion to Islam. Yet, many of these accounts appear to be third-hand, with the author recounting hearsay from various sources. This approach, intended to validate the stories, actually makes them seem less credible and more dubious to me.

What concerns me most about this biography is its attempt to portray Muhammad as a divine figure—humble, wise, and gentle. However, historical accounts often challenge the notion of Muhammad as gentle and humble, leading me to question whether Muslims today are aware of the full history behind Muhammad's ascent to power.

The core teachings of Jesus and his beliefs were quickly left behind as Christian thought evolved after his lifetime. If we examine this history on a broad scale, we notice a tendency for Christianity to drift further from its roots. In today's world, there is a growing awareness and an unprecedented push towards progressiveness. While there are still traditionalists who resist new ways of thinking beyond what they've been taught, this group may not have enough influence to sway the majority. Within the Christian community, there will be a significant increase in historical awareness in the coming years. There will be a growing desire to separate the doctrines added over time from the original intent of Christianity's namesake. Although this may take decades or even centuries, the result is inevitable: a significant shift back to the original form of Christianity. A movement will emerge to peel back layers of doctrine, as if time is being reversed, until only the essence of what Jesus introduced on behalf of God remains, untouched by subsequent claims. As this movement spreads across the United States and Europe, inspiring people to worship as if in Jesus' time, adhering strictly to his teachings, the church will remain strong to guide this transformation. However, as theological perspectives regress, the diversity within Christianity will diminish into greater uniformity in belief and practice. Across regions, denominations, and all divisions, there will be a trend towards similarity rather than difference. History is marked by significant reversals. One example is the early persecution of Christians by the Roman Empire, which later became a Christian stronghold. Our nation has progressed from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The upcoming reversal will take place within Christianity, seeking to undo history and diversity in pursuit of its origins. An essential part of this process will be interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically rather than literally. So, what has transpired since Jesus' time? By looking far back into history, we find the beginnings of Christianity in Judaism, which laid the foundation with monotheism, the notion of a divinely revealed faith, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures, all established by the time Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish community was not united, as it was divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a broad spectrum of common people.

In my view, "The Jungle" illustrates the inherent greed and self-interest that lie within human nature. People tend to prioritize their own well-being and prosperity, often neglecting those who are less fortunate. This theme is evident throughout the novel, particularly in the behavior of the factory owners and managers. Their primary focus is on expanding and enhancing their businesses, disregarding the impact on others or the harm their progress may cause. Upton Sinclair's depiction of the industrial landscape underscores this disregard: "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair illustrates the environmental destruction resulting from pollution and the lack of concern for both people and animals affected by it. The factory owners show no remorse for the smoke and waste produced by their operations.

Furthermore, the owners and managers exhibit little concern for their employees, who toil to generate their wealth. They pursue profit at all costs, sacrificing loyalty and decency: "So from the top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." Workers endure long hours and face abrupt layoffs without compensation or assistance in finding new employment. During the period depicted in "The Jungle," few, if any, laws existed to protect workers' safety or welfare, allowing management to exploit their labor under harsh conditions. Although not explicitly stated, those who toiled and perished in Packingtown were expected to endure the dire circumstances both in and out of the workplace. No organizations existed to support or inform workers, and while unions emerged, they often exacerbated the plight of the laborers by profiting from their struggles. The workers were so oppressed and trapped within the Packingtown system that they were likened to slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Edgar Allan Poe considered "Dream-Land" to be among his finer poetic creations. Within this poem, Poe makes use of the term "Thulé," a reference found in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott links to Virgil. Virgil employed this term to describe an island located to the north of Britain, regarded by the Greeks as the boundary of the known world. While Virgil's use of the term is well-documented, it's important to note that there is a more contemporary influence on Poe's work. Poe showed a keen interest in German authors.

This particular reference underscores Poe's awareness of Goethe's literary contributions. In his book, "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," Karl J. Arndt highlights the parallels between their two poems, suggesting that Poe drew inspiration from Goethe. According to the Oxford Companion to English Literature, Goethe was an esteemed writer, known for his poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts—first in 1808 and later in 1832, the year of Goethe's death. In the second part of "Faust," there is a brief poem titled "The King of Thulé." This poem recounts the story of a king whose wife passes away, leaving him a goblet as a gift. Grief-stricken, the king becomes consumed by heavy drinking and sorrow. In his final moments, he bequeaths his possessions to his children, except for the goblet. He then approaches a cliff, hurls the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and meets his own end. The demeanor of the King of Thulé closely resembles that of the figure in "Dream-Land," perhaps reflecting Poe's own struggles with loss and alcohol. Notably, "Faust" was adapted into a romantic drama by H.P. Grattan in 1842, shortly before Poe's inclusion of "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe refers to Thule on two occasions in his body of work. He mentions "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum," but uses the term twice in "Dream-Land," framing the poem. Viewed collectively, "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be seen as complementary pieces. In "Dream-Land," the narrator describes Thule's landscape as dark and solitary, haunted by the specters of deceased friends, and devoid of color. These elements resonate with the themes in Goethe's "The King of Thule," where the king mourns his wife, feels isolated, and loses his desire to rule or live. The poem's atmosphere suggests that the narrator has entered Goethe's literary world.

Goethe was a prominent figure in literature, and Poe would have been familiar with his work, partly due to his admiration for Tennyson. Poe once remarked on his respect for Tennyson. Beyond this connection, Poe would have encountered Goethe's writings through the numerous reproductions that emerged following the initial publication.

Under the legal framework of California, could a shopper who got hurt after slipping on an applesauce spill in a supermarket potentially receive punitive damages by arguing that the store manager acted with malice, having been informed twice about the spill but not addressing it for thirty minutes because he was having his dinner? It seems unlikely that a judge would immediately dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To argue for such an award, a plaintiff must present evidence showing that the defendant's actions were taken with a willful and conscious disregard for the likely harm their conduct could cause, and that the behavior was despicable. Palmer could assert that Martin should have been aware of the potential harm from not cleaning up the spill, given that other customers had suffered injuries from slipping in the months leading up to Palmer's accident at D&D. Despite this awareness, Martin neglected to ensure the spill was cleaned up. Palmer's claim that Martin’s actions were despicable might be less convincing, yet it remains reasonable considering that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still didn't take proper steps to ensure the store's safety.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 p.m., Rich Wayne, an employee at D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, of an applesauce spill in one of the aisles. Martin, however, responded that he was on his dinner break and couldn't attend to customer complaints. At 5:15 p.m., another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also reported the spill to Martin, receiving the same response. At 5:30 p.m., the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped on the spill and suffered a severe back injury. In the year 2009, five other slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D. Now, Palmer is pursuing both compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and the consideration is on whether to submit a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damages claim.

In California, a plaintiff may recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising from a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice," according to Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute specifies malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or if not intentional, must be "despicable" and done with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Courts have deemed conduct as malicious when done with a conscious disregard for a plaintiff's rights, where the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences," as seen in Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

For as long as she could remember, there was a persistent feeling of yearning within her, an unfulfilled desire that had taken root around the age of 14, as she stepped into her teenage years. Even three years later, at 17, this feeling lingered. She had concluded that her longing was for a person, not an object. Yet, no boys had captured her interest. Some had shown attraction towards her, trying awkwardly to win over her seemingly unyielding heart, but none sparked her interest. She often pondered this puzzling situation, wondering what could lead a teenage girl to feel this way. Despite years of introspection, she had developed theories but nothing substantial enough to consider seriously. So, she continued her life, constantly questioning her desires.

Typically, days spent at home were serene. Her parents were gentle and composed, rarely engaging in disagreements with each other, and seldom with her. The only disputes arose from her asserting her independence and spirited nature. Though born to a calm couple, she balanced their tranquility with her vibrant personality, which, combined with her kindness, made her quite likable.

However, today was an exception to the usual calm. As she moved from one room to another, seeking fresh inspiration, a sudden scream from the kitchen interrupted the tranquility. It was her mother's familiar voice. Startled, she dashed into the kitchen, anxiety building as she called out, "Mom?! Mom, are you okay?!" There, she found her mother on the floor, wincing and repeatedly uttering "Ow" with labored breaths. Rushing to her side, she placed a reassuring hand on her mother, who managed to say, "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to... the hospital." The words were forced and breathy, and her daughter could tell her mother was in severe pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where you need support." Her mother indicated, and at that moment, the daughter felt grateful for her strength training. She lifted her mother into the car, gently laid her in the backseat, and drove.

The hospital greeted them with the familiar blend of antiseptic and anxiety, yet she was too focused on aiding her mother to notice. She hurriedly brought her mother inside, calling for medical help. Concerned staff quickly gathered, placing her mother on a rolling bed and whisking her away for immediate attention, leaving the daughter to wait anxiously.

Her mother had taken a fall from a stepping stool while attempting to retrieve a vase from the highest shelf in their home.

The objective of this research was to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," correlates with a decreased likelihood of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke, as well as mortality from stroke. The aMed diet is an altered form of the Med diet, emphasizing a greater intake of plant-based foods, such as plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (rather than saturated fats), and fish, while reducing the consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have highlighted an inverse relationship between following a Med diet and the risk of overall and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. Moreover, an intervention trial established that the Med diet is more effective than a low-fat diet in aiding weight loss and lowering the total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio among obese individuals. However, past research did not specifically address stroke or stroke-related deaths.

This epidemiological study tracked 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, who had no prior history of CVD or diabetes and were participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the researchers calculated an aMed diet score six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) intended to evaluate nutrient intake over the preceding year. Over 95% of the nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year duration. The FFQs underwent validation studies. Instances of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through examination of medical or hospital records, autopsy, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, incidents were considered "probable" and included, with approximately 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts classified as such. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin consumption, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ. Starting in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was also assessed.

To minimize random variation for individuals and more accurately reflect long-term dietary habits, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were computed (averaging scores from two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could interfere with results) by taking into account age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was employed to evaluate the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Stronger adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as shown by a higher aMed diet score, was linked to a reduced risk of developing CHD and stroke in women. Over a 20-year follow-up period, there were 2391 new cases of CHD, 1763 new cases of stroke, and 1077 deaths from cardiovascular disease (including both fatal CHD and strokes). Women in the highest aMed quintile faced a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign declares: "Hitler is alive in Burma."

Ellen Page, known for her role in the movie Juno, stands solitary at a street corner, gripping a cardboard sign with those unsettling words scrawled in Sharpie. Burma, which is also referred to as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation governed by a harsh military junta that seized power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, the country saw its first significant public demonstrations in a decade. These were spearheaded by numerous Burmese monks and came to be known as the “Saffron Revolution,” named after the saffron-colored robes the monks wore. Initially, the government reluctantly permitted the peaceful protests, but as the public's involvement grew, tensions intensified. The situation escalated into what many viewed as a conflict between the monks and the military, with the junta raiding monasteries across the nation. Foreign journalists were detained, and Japanese photojournalist Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, merely for attending a protest. While official reports claim 13 fatalities, Colonel Hla Win, an army defector, suggested that the actual number of deaths was much higher, potentially in the thousands.

These acts of brutality are not unprecedented. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress opposition to maintain control. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine selection to justify their absolute authority. Similarly, Japanese emperors were seen as deities destined to guide their people. In the contemporary era, President George W. Bush reportedly held regular discussions with Ted Haggard, the leader of an organization named Stupid People Worldwide, affiliated with the Republican Party.

Historical cases of such repression include the June 4, 1989, protests at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, workers, and students rallied against government authoritarianism. The death toll from this event varies, with Chinese government estimates at 200-300 deaths, while the Chinese Red Cross reported between 2,000-3,000 fatalities. Another grim example is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, during which Hutu militias, supported by the Rwandan government, executed a systematic massacre targeting Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of ethnicity. The atrocities committed under Hitler’s ‘Third Reich,’ during which Jews were systematically exterminated across several countries, represent another extreme case of such oppression.

Duke Ellington's remarkable impact on jazz is largely attributed to his enduring career and his innovative skill in orchestrating his band. While Ellington's piano presence is understated in many of the pieces chosen for this analysis, his prowess as a composer shines through his ability to craft intricate and layered compositions that highlighted his band members' talents. He constructed a musical environment where soloists could improvise freely while also composing tightly orchestrated segments that leveraged each musician's unique style to bring out musical concepts. Through this approach, he accentuated the orchestra's overall tone, creating unified and original melodies tailored to each piece. His exceptional understanding of individual musicians' sounds, combined with their collective harmony in an expanding ensemble, allowed him to produce some of jazz's most imaginative and outstanding works.

The Grove Music dictionary, when exploring Ellington's distinctive sound and inventiveness, points to Creole Love Call as an example of his use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This early piece illustrates Ellington's use of voice to add texture and color independent of lyrics. Creole Love Call also showcases Ellington's knack for complementing his soloists' styles, a characteristic evident throughout his career. This deliberate twelve-bar blues piece unfolds through six choruses, as follows:

Chorus 1: Features a call and response between voice and reeds, starting with a smooth, melodic voice that transitions to a coarser tone by the end.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo expands on the main melody, emphasizing several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: A high-register clarinet solo is supported by a discreet syncopated piano line.
Chorus 4: The entire band mirrors the first chorus with a call and response between the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The piece reaches its climax as the reeds initiate the call and response in a higher register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: Revisits the first chorus's structure, with call and response between voice and reeds. Here, the voice employs the "growl" technique, performing as an instrument.
Tag: Concludes with a brief vocal run and a dissonant, novel trombone ending.

Ellington's integration of voice to enhance the tonal diversity of the piece exemplifies a stylistic characteristic that permeates his body of work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington blends his tight orchestration skills with his sensitivity to tone color. The piece features a call and response between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing, intertwining Miley’s vocal-like trumpet playing with Cox’s instrumental vocal style to create a complex and harmonious sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) further explores these ideas, with Ellington using Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a stalwart of his orchestra, to introduce the melody on muted trombone to great effect.

What causes organisms to evolve in the ways they do? Are there particular limitations or factors that guide evolutionary changes? Even back in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson remarked that "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms," a statement that holds true today. In recent years, mathematical modeling has been increasingly applied to various aspects of mollusk shell formation throughout both individual development and evolutionary history (such as in the work of Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research investigates how mathematical modeling of developmental and evolutionary changes in the Prunum species, combined with experimental studies, can help clarify the mechanisms driving the direction and extent of evolutionary-developmental changes. By using X-ray images of Prunum species, we identified quantitative parameters that could model both hypothetical and actual shell shapes. These parameters were input into the software CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We then created models of hypothetical shell forms to explore the limits of potential morphological changes in Prunum. These findings are being integrated with experimental and descriptive studies to gain a deeper understanding of large-scale evolutionary events in this group.

Think of a shell as a tube moving through 360 degrees of space over time. The turns of a coiled shell are known as whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis, the columella, runs through the shell's central column. Whorls can expand at different speeds, and they are separated by a line called a suture. Typically, the largest whorl is the final one, also known as the body whorl. The spire includes all the whorls except for the last one. The spire’s tip is the apex, and the opposite end is called the base. The animal emerges from its shell through an opening termed the aperture.

Shells can be observed from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. (The "usual" way to view a shell is apertural, with the aperture facing the observer and the apex pointing upward.)

To count whorls, one starts by looking at the shell from the apical view and identifying where the first suture begins. A line is then drawn to divide the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and approximated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a sequence of openings that move through time and space as the animal constructs its shell. The path of the aperture can be traced using coordinates for the center of each whorl’s aperture along with the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This path can be represented in both graphical and mathematical forms. Once a mathematical model is constructed, it's possible to adjust the parameters and alter the mollusk’s shell-forming process.

In Indonesia, the rates of neonatal and infant mortality have not seen significant changes over the past decade. The country is progressing towards several Millennium Development Goals, such as those related to water and sanitation. However, the necessary advancements in child and maternal health are not being achieved at the pace required to meet the targets set for 2015. The reasons for these deficiencies will be elaborated on, highlighting the importance of enhancing the overall health system instead of focusing solely on specific program interventions.

There have been advancements in ensuring skilled health workers are present at births, with 72% of deliveries now attended by such professionals. However, this figure also includes traditional practitioners like midwives, who are not equipped to handle medical complications during childbirth, contributing to the high number of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage. Therefore, while progress in this area is reflected in the statistics, it presents a somewhat deceptive picture, indicating that substantial efforts are still needed. Moreover, there is a reduction in the proportion of children under five with diarrhea receiving treatment from healthcare professionals. Although comprehensive data on postnatal care is lacking, it is evident that this remains a significant concern nationwide.

Cesarean section rates are lower than expected, approximately 4%. This statistic also highlights another issue: the disparity in healthcare access between urban and rural areas. In urban areas, the cesarean section rate is 7%, compared to just 2% in rural regions, underscoring the uneven distribution of healthcare services. Additionally, there is a noticeable gap in healthcare service utilization between the wealthiest and poorest segments of the population, with a 27% difference, indicating that the poor face greater barriers to accessing healthcare, likely due to the financial burden involved.

When considering the next steps to enhance neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to effectively address the shortfall in service provision. Should Indonesia implement specific program strategies or focus on strengthening the health system as a whole without centering on maternal and child healthcare before and after pregnancy? Program-specific strategies are appealing as they offer targeted and manageable objectives, often yielding quicker results. However, there are potential drawbacks. A significant concern is that concentrating resources on one area can divert funding from other sectors, leading to an imbalance in resource allocation (as seen with the impact of international funding for HIV/AIDS on family planning services). Moreover, running several parallel programs can lead to service duplication and a lack of coordination, increasing the administrative burden for supplies and fund management.

Over the past century, the landscape of Popular Music has expanded to encompass countless genres, making it challenging to compile a comprehensive list. Adding to the complexity, nearly every genre—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—has given rise to numerous sub-genres and even further subdivisions. Among these, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has arguably evolved into one of the most varied and expressive categories of popular music over the past four decades. Its expressiveness stems from its ability to convey a broad spectrum of emotions, albeit often leaning toward the more somber end. In terms of diversity, soon after its inception, the genre's inherent flexibility was recognized, leading to the creation of various sub-genres and sub-sub-genres, a process that continues to this day.

Currently, the heavy metal scene has reached a level of diversity where pinpointing a precise definition of what constitutes heavy metal is challenging. It has absorbed numerous elements from other genres, yet like all things, it originated from a specific point. To fully appreciate the metal music prevalent today, one must first grasp the essence of the metal movement and why it transcends being just a genre.

In various respects, metal is a movement characterized by its dark themes. It can be described as "music of more"—more bass, volume, intensity, and theatricality. It moves away from primitiveness, showcasing skilled musicianship; members of metal bands are adept with their instruments, and this expertise is evident in their music. Unsurprisingly, metal is also a movement with significant drug influences. The psychedelic drug surge of the mid-1970s led to increasingly experimental music, with artists using substances as a catalyst for creating groundbreaking and otherworldly records. Metal's dark and visceral qualities stood out in the music scene, contrasting with the predominantly lighter themes in popular music. Later metal generations drew inspiration from the dark and intense elements that were prominent during the Romantic Era. Lyrics reflecting this darkness are emblematic of the movement, such as those by Byrne.

The lyrics of "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles showcase their darker side, depicting a tumultuous experience often associated with drug use. This track is sometimes cited as one of the earliest Heavy Metal songs, crafted in response to a Rolling Stones track that also explored heavier, darker themes. The Beatles aimed to demonstrate that they could match the intensity of the Stones, leading to the inclusion of this song on The White Album.
